english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Twin Brilliance
  author: Lee In-ro
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The world believes that the arts of longevity and eternal youth can be learned. This is mistaken. The immortals breathe wind and drink dew, roaming freely through the eight directions, untouched by worldly afflictions. Their lives align with the cycles of heaven and earth itself. How could those who waste away through starvation and gather herbs ever attain such heights?

    The bones of ancient sages like Wang Qiao and Chi Songzi, the transcendent essence of the isles of Penglai and Yingzhou—these spring from nature itself. They do not strive for longevity, yet longevity comes of its own accord.

    Consider material things: gold and jade endure longest. They neither rot in mud nor char in flame. Their unyielding substance cannot be compared to common copper or corroded iron. Among plants, the pine and cypress live longest. Though nourished by rain and dew, by day and night like other vegetation, when frost cracks the earth, they alone remain verdant and unchanged. Surely this transcends mere mushrooms growing on decaying soil. Among creatures, the tortoise and crane live longest. Emerging from the womb, breathing toward the sun, their calls reach heaven itself, their bones so light they rest upon lotus leaves. They are no ordinary fish or bird.

    Thus all things that excel among their kind and bear the name of longevity in this world attain it through nature itself, never through human artifice. And this applies equally to people.

    Consider now the Grand Commander of Changwon. He has served through four dynasties, maintaining unwavering integrity through calm and crisis alike. Elevated to high office, he recommended worthy talents and brought stability to the realm. Before reaching seventy, he petitioned for retirement and was granted the honor of relinquishing his post. He cherished a magnificent tree atop a remote peak south of the Hall of Reverent Literature, where he built a pavilion beside it. There he spent his days with eight other esteemed elders of our time, finding joy in the zither, chess, poetry, and wine, following the ancient customs of the Society of Genuine Simplicity.

    Once a scholar named Zhang Ziba addressed the gathering: "Long ago, Han Tuizhi lamented his premature aging, saying he could no longer distinguish people's faces. Du Fu also sighed, 'Viewing flowers is like gazing through mist.' Yet our Lord's violet eyes gleam like lightning itself. He surveys distant peaks beyond the parting clouds as clearly as objects in his palm. Should we not name this hall 'Twin Brilliance'?" All agreed it was perfectly fitting.

    Soon after, the Commander's brother, the Grand Preceptor, also retired from office to join him in this seclusion. At their gatherings, sons and nephews descended in golden regalia and official robes like phoenixes spreading their wings, like ancient trees casting unified shade—a vision of the immortals on Mount Guasha or the five sages by the Fen River, such as mortals rarely witness.

    They commissioned a painter to create the "Portrait of Eastern Sages," which was engraved in stone for posterity. Even those dwelling in distant lands or hidden valleys, upon seeing this image, feel a cool breeze sweep through them.

    Zhang Liang, that hero of the Han, wielded his three-inch tongue to gain the rank of ten-thousand-household marquis, yet knowing he had reached the pinnacle of common station, he sought to follow Chi Songzi but never fulfilled that wish. Xie An, the renowned minister of the southern lands, defeated the armies of Qin and secured the Jin dynasty as firmly as Mount Tai, yet after dreaming of a white rooster, he never again ascended the Eastern Mountain to view the moon.

    But our Lord has achieved both—his service to the throne already accomplished, his joy in nature fully realized. This is the "possession of two perfections," rare in all of history. His transcendent bearing and Daoist essence seem heaven-born. His complexion remains youthful as an infant's, his voice resonant as metal and stone. Not the slightest decay marks him, nor can worldly concerns disturb his spirit. Thus his years are boundless, and the transformations of the world—blue seas becoming mulberry fields—pass before him as mere morning and evening.

    Zhuangzi said: "Without effort, one becomes refined; without practicing longevity arts, one endures." This is precisely what is meant here. Who knows but that one day he will soar beyond the six directions, shake off worldly dust, and sporting with golden youths and jade maidens, play upon the peaks of Langfeng and the gardens of Xuanpu, before riding a crane back to his homeland and waving farewell to all the world?

    I have humbly knelt before him and received his words. I respectfully record this account.
